Analyze the following PlantUML use case model and detect if it contains any antipatterns.
Base your analysis solely on the model provided. Do not use any outside knowledge.


PlantUML Model:
@startuml
' Version 1 – contains Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

actor Author
actor Reader
actor Editor

rectangle "E-Book Publishing System" {
  usecase "Upload Manuscript" as UC1
  usecase "Publish E-Book" as UC2
  usecase "Validate Manuscript Format" as UC3
  usecase "Browse Catalog" as UC4
  usecase "Purchase E-Book" as UC5
  usecase "Review Manuscript" as UC6
}

Author --> UC1
Author --> UC2
UC2 ..> UC3 : <<include>>
Reader --> UC4
Reader --> UC5
Editor --> UC6

@enduml


Answer:
Antipattern Detected: Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

   Constructs Involved: Publish E-Book, Validate Manuscript Format
   Explanation: The use case "Validate Manuscript Format" is an inclusion use case that is included by only one use case ("Publish E-Book"). It is not associated with any actor directly — no actor interacts with it. It does not include or extend any other use case, nor is it extended by any use case, and it has no generalization relationships. "Validate Manuscript Format" does not represent a complete, independently meaningful service to any user; it is merely a decomposed sub-step of the "Publish E-Book" process. This constitutes the Functional Decomposition antipattern because the include relationship is being misused to break a use case into procedural steps rather than to share genuinely reusable, actor-facing behavior.
